0 -14 Td
() Tj
0 -14 Td
(This project predicts whether an individual earns >50K per year using the Adult Census) Tj
0 -14 Td
(Income dataset. The intended stakeholder is a workforce policy or HR analytics team that) Tj
0 -14 Td
(needs priority ranking rather than a perfect deterministic rule. A binary classifier is) Tj
0 -14 Td
(appropriate because the operational decision is whether an individual likely belongs in a) Tj
0 -14 Td
(higher-income segment, not exact income estimation.) Tj
0 -14 Td
() Tj
0 -14 Td
(The dataset contains 32,561 records and 14 predictors \(Kohavi, 1996; Dua and Graff, 2019\).) Tj
0 -14 Td
(The target is imbalanced: 75.9% <=50K and 24.1% >50K \(Figure 1\), so raw accuracy is not a) Tj
0 -14 Td
(safe primary metric. Before any modelling, success criteria were fixed as:) Tj
0 -14 Td
() Tj
0 -14 Td
(- weighted F1 >= 0.82) Tj
0 -14 Td
(- positive-class recall \(>50K\) >= 0.75) Tj
0 -14 Td
(- calibration quality suitable for threshold-based policy decisions) Tj
0 -14 Td
() Tj
0 -14 Td
(The final model is a tuned HistGradientBoosting classifier with operating threshold 0.36.) Tj
0 -14 Td
(On the untouched test set, it achieves weighted F1 0.862, recall 0.784, PR-AUC 0.828,) Tj
0 -14 Td
(ROC-AUC 0.926, and calibration error \(ECE\) 0.014. Relative to the logistic baseline,) Tj
0 -14 Td
(this is a +0.041 absolute F1 gain, or approximately +5.0% relative improvement.) Tj
0 -14 Td
() Tj
0 -14 Td
